# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ebpf-security-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] The **Berkeley Packet Filter** (**BPF**; also **BSD Packet Filter**, **classic BPF** or **cBPF**) is a network tap mechanism and packet filter which permits computer network packets to be captured and filtered at the operating system level.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] It provides a raw interface to data link layers, permitting raw link-layer packets to be sent and received, and allows a userspace process to supply a filter program that specifies which packets it wants to receive.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] For example, a tcpdump process may want to receive only packets that initiate a TCP connection.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF returns only packets that pass the filter that the process supplies.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] This avoids copying unwanted packets from the operating system kernel to the process, greatly improving performance.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] The filter program is in the form of instructions for a virtual machine, which are interpreted, or compiled into machine code by a just-in-time (JIT) mechanism and executed, in the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is used by programs that need to, among other things, analyze network traffic.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] If the driver for the network interface supports promiscuous mode, it allows the interface to be put into that mode so that all packets on the network can be received, even those destined to other hosts.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] The BPF filtering mechanism is available on most Unix-like operating systems.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is sometimes used to refer to just the filtering mechanism, rather than to the entire interface.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Some systems, such as Linux and Tru64 UNIX, provide a raw interface to the data link layer other than the BPF raw interface but use the BPF filtering mechanisms for that raw interface.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] The Linux kernel provides an extended version of the BPF filtering mechanism, called eBPF, which uses a JIT mechanism, and which is used for packet filtering, as well as for other purposes in the kernel. eBPF is also available for Microsoft Windows.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] The original paper was written by Steven McCanne and Van Jacobson in 1992 while at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF provides pseudo-devices that can be bound to a network interface; reads from the device will read buffers full of packets received on the network interface, and writes to the device will inject packets on the network interface.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] While one copy remains in the receipt path for user processes, this preserves the independence of different BPF device consumers, as well as allowing the packing of headers into the BPF buffer rather than copying complete packet data.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF's filtering capabilities are implemented as an interpreter for a machine language for the BPF virtual machine, a 32-bit machine with fixed-length instructions, one accumulator, and one index register.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Programs in that language can fetch data from the packet, perform arithmetic operations on data from the packet, and compare the results against constants or against data in the packet or test bits in the results, accepting or rejecting the packet based on the results of those tests.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is often extended by "overloading" the load (ld) and store (str) instructions.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Traditional Unix-like BPF implementations can be used in userspace, despite being written for kernel-space.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] This is accomplished using preprocessor conditions.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Since version 3.18, the Linux kernel includes an extended BPF virtual machine with ten 64-bit registers, termed eBPF.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] It can be used for non-networking purposes, such as for attaching eBPF programs to various tracepoints.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Since kernel version 3.19, eBPF filters can be attached to sockets, and, since kernel version 4.1, to traffic control classifiers for the ingress and egress networking data path.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] The original and obsolete version has been retroactively renamed to *classic BPF* (*cBPF*).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Nowadays, the Linux kernel runs eBPF only and loaded cBPF bytecode is transparently translated into an eBPF representation in the kernel before program execution.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] All bytecode is verified before running to prevent denial-of-service attacks.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Until Linux 5.3, the verifier prohibited the use of loops, to prevent potentially unbounded execution times; loops with bounded execution time are now permitted in more recent kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Some projects use BPF instruction sets or execution techniques different from the originals.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Some platforms, including FreeBSD, NetBSD, and WinPcap, use a just-in-time compiler (JIT) to convert BPF instructions into native code in order to improve performance.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Linux includes a BPF JIT compiler which is disabled by default.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Kernel-mode interpreters for that same virtual machine language are used in raw data link layer mechanisms in other operating systems, such as Tru64 Unix, and for socket filters in the Linux kernel and in the WinPcap and Npcap packet capture mechanism.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] That interpreter can also be used when reading a file containing packets captured using pcap.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Another user-mode interpreter is *uBPF*, which supports JIT and eBPF (without cBPF).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Its code has been reused to provide eBPF support in non-Linux systems.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Microsoft's *eBPF on Windows* builds on uBPF and the PREVAIL formal verifier.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] *rBPF*, a Rust rewrite of uBPF, is used by the Solana blockchain platform as the execution engine.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Classic BPF is generally emitted by a program from some very high-level textual rule describing the pattern to match.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] One such representation is found in libpcap.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Classic BPF and eBPF can also be written either directly as machine code, or using an assembly language for a textual representation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Notable assemblers include Linux kernel's `bpf_asm` tool (cBPF), `bpfc` (cBPF), and the `ubpf` assembler (eBPF).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] The `bpftool` command can also act as a disassembler for both flavors of BPF.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] The assembly languages are not necessarily compatible with each other.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] eBPF bytecode has recently become a target of higher-level languages.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] LLVM added eBPF support in 2014, and GCC followed in 2019.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Both toolkits allow compiling C and other supported languages to eBPF.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] A subset of P4 can also be compiled into eBPF using BCC, an LLVM-based compiler kit.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] The Spectre attack could leverage the Linux kernel's eBPF interpreter or JIT compiler to extract data from other kernel processes.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] A JIT hardening feature in the kernel mitigates this vulnerability.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/berkeley-packet-filter] Chinese computer security group Pangu Lab said the NSA used BPF to conceal network communications as part of a complex Linux backdoor.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a combination of the two traditional approaches to translation to machine code: ahead-of-time compilation (AOT), and interpretation, which combines some advantages and drawbacks of both.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Roughly, JIT compilation combines the speed of compiled code with the flexibility of interpretation, with the overhead of an interpreter and the additional overhead of compiling and linking (not just interpreting).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a form of dynamic compilation, and allows adaptive optimization such as dynamic recompilation and microarchitecture-specific speedups.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Interpretation and JIT compilation are particularly suited for dynamic programming languages, as the runtime system can handle late-bound data types and enforce security guarantees.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] The earliest published JIT compiler is generally attributed to work on LISP by John McCarthy in 1960.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Another early example was by Ken Thompson, who in 1968 gave one of the first applications of regular expressions, here for pattern matching in the text editor QED.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by JITing to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] An influential technique for deriving compiled code from interpretation was pioneered by James G.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Mitchell in 1970, which he implemented for the experimental language *LC²*.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] 1980) pioneered new aspects of JIT compilations.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] For example, translation to machine code was done on demand, and the result was cached for later use.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] When memory became scarce, the system would delete some of this code and regenerate it when it was needed again.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Sun's Self language improved these techniques extensively and was at one point the fastest Smalltalk system in the world, achieving up to half the speed of optimized C but with a fully object-oriented programming language.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Self was abandoned by Sun, but the research went into the Java language.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] The term "Just-in-time compilation" was borrowed from the manufacturing term "Just in time" and popularized by Java, with James Gosling using the term from 1993.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Currently JITing is used by most implementations of the Java virtual machine, as HotSpot builds on, and extensively uses, this research base.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] The HP project Dynamo was an experimental JIT compiler where the "bytecode" format and the machine code format were the same; the system optimized PA-8000 machine code.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] In November 2020, PHP 8.0 introduced a JIT compiler.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] In October 2024, CPython introduced an experimental JIT compiler.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] In a bytecode-compiled system, source code is translated to an intermediate representation known as bytecode.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Bytecode is not the machine code for any particular computer, and may be portable among computer architectures.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] The bytecode may then be interpreted by, or run on a virtual machine.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] The JIT compiler reads the bytecodes in many sections (or in full, rarely) and compiles them dynamically into machine code so the program can run faster.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] This can be done per-file, per-function or even on any arbitrary code fragment; the code can be compiled when it is about to be executed (hence the name "just-in-time"), and then cached and reused later without needing to be recompiled.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] By contrast, a traditional *interpreted virtual machine* will simply interpret the bytecode, generally with much lower performance.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Some *interpreter*s even interpret source code, without the step of first compiling to bytecode, with even worse performance.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] *Statically-compiled code* or *native code* is compiled prior to deployment.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] A *dynamic compilation environment* is one in which the compiler can be used during execution.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] The deployed bytecode is portable, unlike native code.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Since the runtime has control over the compilation, like interpreted bytecode, it can run in a secure sandbox.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Compilers from bytecode to machine code are easier to write, because the portable bytecode compiler has already done much of the work.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] JIT code generally offers far better performance than interpreters.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] The system is able to collect statistics about how the program is actually running in the environment it is in, and it can rearrange and recompile for optimum performance.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] However, some static compilers can also take profile information as input.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] The system can do global code optimizations (e.g. inlining of library functions) without losing the advantages of dynamic linking and without the overheads inherent to static compilers and linkers.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] With just-in-time compilation in many cases this processing can be moved out of loops, often giving large increases of speed.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Although this is possible with statically compiled garbage collected languages, a bytecode system can more easily rearrange executed code for better cache utilization.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] However, a special type of "JIT" may potentially *not* target the physical machine's CPU architecture, but rather an optimized VM bytecode where limitations on raw machine code prevail, especially where that bytecode's VM eventually leverages a JIT to native code.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] JIT causes a slight to noticeable delay in the initial execution of an application, due to the time taken to load and compile the input code.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Sometimes this delay is called "startup time delay" or "warm-up time".
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] In general, the more optimization JIT performs, the better the code it will generate, but the initial delay will also increase.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] A JIT compiler therefore has to make a trade-off between the compilation time and the quality of the code it hopes to generate.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Startup time can include increased IO-bound operations in addition to JIT compilation: for example, the *rt.jar* class data file for the Java virtual machine (JVM) is 40 MB and the JVM must seek a lot of data in this contextually huge file.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] One possible optimization, used by Sun's HotSpot Java virtual machine, is to combine interpretation and JIT compilation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] The application code is initially interpreted, but the JVM monitors which sequences of bytecode are frequently executed and translates them to machine code for direct execution on the hardware.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] For bytecode which is executed only a few times, this saves the compilation time and reduces the initial latency; for frequently executed bytecode, JIT compilation is used to run at high speed, after an initial phase of slow interpretation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Further, since a program spends most time executing a minority of its code, the reduced compilation time is significant.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Finally, during the initial code interpretation, execution statistics can be collected before compilation, which helps to perform better optimization.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] The correct tradeoff can vary due to circumstances.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] For example, Sun's Java virtual machine has two major modes—client and server.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] In client mode, minimal compilation and optimization is performed, to reduce startup time.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] In server mode, extensive compilation and optimization is performed, to maximize performance once the application is running by sacrificing startup time.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Other Java just-in-time compilers have used a runtime measurement of the number of times a method has executed combined with the bytecode size of a method as a heuristic to decide when to compile.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Still another uses the number of times executed combined with the detection of loops.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] In general, it is much harder to accurately predict which methods to optimize in short-running applications than in long-running ones.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Native Image Generator (Ngen) by Microsoft is another approach at reducing the initial delay.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Ngen pre-compiles (or "pre-JITs") bytecode in a Common Intermediate Language image into machine native code.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] As a result, no runtime compilation is needed. .NET Framework 2.0 shipped with Visual Studio 2005 runs Ngen on all of the Microsoft dynamic-link library (DLL) files right after installing.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Pre-jitting provides a way to reduce startup time.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] However, the quality of code it generates may be lower than the one that is JITed, for the same reasons why code compiled statically, without profile-guided optimization, cannot be as good as JIT compiled code in the extreme case: the lack of profiling data to drive, for instance, inline caching.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] There also exist Java implementations that combine an AOT (ahead-of-time) compiler with either a JIT compiler (Excelsior JET) or interpreter (GNU Compiler for Java).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation may not reliably achieve its goal, namely entering a steady state of improved performance after a short initial warmup period.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Across eight different virtual machines, Barrett et al.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] (2017) measured six widely used microbenchmarks which are commonly used by virtual machine implementors as optimisation targets, running them repeatedly within a single process execution.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Even where an improved steady-state was reached, it sometimes took many hundreds of iterations.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] (2022) instead focused on the HotSpot virtual machine but with a much wider array of benchmarks, finding that 10.9% of process executions failed to reach a steady state of performance, and 43.5% of benchmarks did not consistently attain a steady state across multiple executions.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation fundamentally uses executable data, and thus poses security challenges and possible exploits.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Implementation of JIT compilation consists of compiling source code or byte code to machine code and executing it.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] This is generally done directly in memory: the JIT compiler outputs the machine code directly into memory and immediately executes it, rather than outputting it to disk and then invoking the code as a separate program, as in usual ahead of time compilation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] In modern architectures this runs into a problem due to executable space protection: arbitrary memory cannot be executed, as otherwise there is a potential security hole.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Thus memory must be marked as executable; for security reasons this should be done *after* the code has been written to memory, and marked read-only, as writable/executable memory is a security hole (see W^X).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] For instance Firefox's JIT compiler for JavaScript introduced this protection in a release version with Firefox 46.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] JIT spraying is a class of computer security exploits that use JIT compilation for heap spraying: the resulting memory is then executable, which allows an exploit if execution can be moved into the heap.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation can be applied to some programs, or can be used for certain capacities, particularly dynamic capacities such as regular expressions.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] For example, a text editor may compile a regular expression provided at runtime to machine code to allow faster matching: this cannot be done ahead of time, as the pattern is only provided at runtime.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Several modern runtime environments rely on JIT compilation for high-speed code execution, including most implementations of Java, together with Microsoft's .NET.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Similarly, many regular-expression libraries feature JIT compilation of regular expressions, either to bytecode or to machine code.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is also used in some emulators, in order to translate machine code from one CPU architecture to another.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] A common implementation of JIT compilation is to first have AOT compilation to bytecode (virtual machine code), known as *bytecode compilation*, and then have JIT compilation to machine code (dynamic compilation), rather than interpretation of the bytecode.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] This improves the runtime performance compared to interpretation, at the cost of lag due to compilation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilers translate continuously, as with interpreters, but caching of compiled code minimizes lag on future execution of the same code during a given run.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/just-in-time-compilation] Since only part of the program is compiled, there is significantly less lag than if the entire program were compiled prior to execution.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A **kernel** is a computer program at the core of a computer's operating system that always has complete control over everything in the system.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is also responsible for preventing and mitigating conflicts between different processes.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] It is the portion of the operating system that is always resident in memory and facilitates interactions between hardware and software components.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A full kernel controls all hardware resources (e.g.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] I/O, memory, cryptography) via device drivers, arbitrates conflicts between processes concerning such resources, and optimizes the use of common resources, such as CPU, cache, file systems, and network sockets.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] On most systems, the kernel is one of the first programs loaded on startup (after the bootloader).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] It handles the rest of startup as well as memory, peripherals, and input/output (I/O) requests from software, translating them into data-processing instructions for the central processing unit.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The critical code of the kernel is usually loaded into a separate area of memory, which is protected from access by application software or other less critical parts of the operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel performs its tasks, such as scheduling processes, managing hardware devices such as the hard disk, and handling interrupts, in this protected kernel space.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In contrast, application programs such as browsers, word processors, or audio or video players use a separate area of memory, user space.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This prevents user data and kernel data from interfering with each other and causing instability and slowness, as well as preventing malfunctioning applications from affecting other applications or crashing the entire operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Even in systems where the kernel is included in application address spaces, memory protection is used to prevent unauthorized applications from modifying the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel's interface is a low-level abstraction layer.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a process requests a service from the kernel, it must invoke a system call, usually through a wrapper function.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] There are different kernel architecture designs.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels run entirely in a single address space with the CPU executing in supervisor mode, mainly for speed.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels run most but not all of their services in user space, like user processes do, mainly for resilience and modularity.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] MINIX 3 is a notable example of microkernel design.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some kernels, such as the Linux kernel, are both monolithic and modular, since they can insert and remove loadable kernel modules at runtime.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This central component of a computer system is responsible for executing programs.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel takes responsibility for deciding at any time which of the many running programs should be allocated to the processor or processors.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Random-access memory (RAM) is used to store both program instructions and data.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Typically, both need to be present in memory for a program to execute.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often, multiple programs will want memory access, frequently demanding more memory than the computer has available.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is responsible for deciding which memory each process can use, and determining what to do when insufficient memory is available.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] I/O devices include, but are not limited to, peripherals such as keyboards, mice, disk drives, printers, USB devices, network adapters, and display devices.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel provides convenient methods for applications to use these devices, which are typically abstracted by the kernel so that applications do not need to know their implementation details.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Key aspects necessary in resource management are defining the execution domain (address space) and the protection mechanism used to mediate access to the resources within a domain.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Kernels also provide methods for synchronization and inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] These implementations may be located within the kernel itself or the kernel can also rely on other processes it is running.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Although the kernel must provide IPC in order to provide access to the facilities provided by each other, kernels must also provide running programs with a method to make requests to access these facilities.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel is also responsible for context switching between processes or threads.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel has full access to the system's memory and must allow processes to safely access this memory as they require it.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often the first step in doing this is virtual addressing, usually achieved by paging and/or segmentation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual addressing allows the kernel to make a given physical address appear to be another address, the virtual address.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual address spaces may be different for different processes; the memory that one process accesses at a particular (virtual) address may be different memory from what another process accesses at the same address.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This allows every program to behave as if it is the only one (apart from the kernel) running and thus prevents applications from crashing each other.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] On many systems, a program's virtual address may refer to data that is not currently in memory.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The layer of indirection provided by virtual addressing allows the operating system to use other data stores, like a hard drive, to store what would otherwise have to remain in main memory (RAM).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] As a result, operating systems can allow programs to use more memory than the system has physically available.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a program needs data that is not currently in RAM, the CPU signals to the kernel that this has happened, and the kernel responds by writing the contents of an inactive memory block to disk (if necessary) and replacing it with the data requested by the program.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The program can then be resumed from the point where it was stopped.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This scheme is generally known as demand paging.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Virtual addressing also allows creation of virtual partitions of memory in two disjoint areas, one being reserved for the kernel (kernel space) and the other for the applications (user space).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The applications are not permitted by the processor to address kernel memory, thus preventing an application from damaging the running kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This fundamental partition of memory space has contributed much to the current designs of actual general-purpose kernels and is almost universal in such systems, although some research kernels (e.g., Singularity) take other approaches.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] To perform useful functions, processes need access to the peripherals connected to the computer, which are controlled by the kernel through device drivers.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A device driver is a computer program encapsulating, monitoring and controlling a hardware device (via its hardware/software interface (HSI)) on behalf of the OS.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] It provides the operating system with an API, procedures and information about how to control and communicate with a certain piece of hardware.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Device drivers are an important and vital dependency for all OS and their applications.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The design goal of a driver is abstraction; the function of the driver is to translate the OS-mandated abstract function calls (programming calls) into device-specific calls.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In theory, a device should work correctly with a suitable driver.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Device drivers are used for e.g. host adapters, video cards, sound cards, printers, scanners, modems, and network interface controllers.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] For example, to show the user something on the screen, an application would make a request to the kernel, which would forward the request to its display driver, which is then responsible for actually plotting the character/pixel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A kernel must maintain a list of available devices.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In plug-and-play systems, a device manager first performs a scan on different peripheral buses, such as Peripheral Component Interconnect (PCI) or Universal Serial Bus (USB), to detect installed devices, then searches for the appropriate drivers.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] As device management is a very OS-specific topic, these drivers are handled differently by each kind of kernel design, but in every case, the kernel has to provide the I/O to allow drivers to physically access their devices through some port or memory location.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Important decisions have to be made when designing the device management system, as in some designs accesses may involve context switches, making the operation very CPU-intensive and easily causing a significant performance overhead.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In computing, a system call is how a process requests a service from an operating system's kernel that it does not normally have permission to run.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] System calls provide the interface between a process and the operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most operations interacting with the system require permissions not available to a user-level process, e.g., I/O performed with a device present on the system, or any form of communication with other processes requires the use of system calls.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A system call is a mechanism that is used by the application program to request a service from the operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] They use a machine-code instruction that causes the processor to change mode.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] An example would be from supervisor mode to protected mode.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is where the operating system performs actions like accessing hardware devices or the memory management unit.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Generally the operating system provides a library that sits between the operating system and normal user programs.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Usually it is a C library such as Glibc or Windows API.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The library handles the low-level details of passing information to the kernel and switching to supervisor mode.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] System calls include close, open, read, wait and write.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] To actually perform useful work, a process must be able to access the services provided by the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is implemented differently by each kernel, but most provide a C library or an API, which in turn invokes the related kernel functions.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The method of invoking the kernel function varies from kernel to kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] If memory isolation is in use, it is impossible for a user process to call the kernel directly, because that would be a violation of the processor's access control rules.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] An important consideration in the design of a kernel is the support it provides for protection from faults (fault tolerance) and from malicious behaviours (security).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] These two aspects are usually not clearly distinguished, and the adoption of this distinction in the kernel design leads to the rejection of a hierarchical structure for protection.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Support for hierarchical protection domains is typically implemented using CPU modes.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many kernels implement "capabilities", i.e., objects provided to user code that allow limited access to an underlying object managed by the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A common example is file handling: a file is a representation of information stored on a permanent storage device.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel may be able to perform many different operations, including read, write, delete or execute, but a user-level application may only be permitted to perform some of these operations (e.g., it may only be allowed to read the file).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A common implementation of this is for the kernel to provide an object to the application (typically called a "file handle") that the application may then invoke operations on, the validity of which the kernel checks at the time the operation is requested.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Such a system may be extended to cover all objects that the kernel manages, and indeed to objects provided by other user applications.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] An efficient and simple way to provide hardware support of capabilities is to delegate to the memory management unit (MMU) the responsibility of checking access-rights for every memory access, a mechanism called capability-based addressing.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most commercial computer architectures lack such MMU support for capabilities; the Capability Hardware Enhanced RISC Instructions (CHERI) project is developing capability-based mechanisms for several architectures.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] An alternative approach is to simulate capabilities using commonly supported hierarchical domains.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In this approach, each protected object must reside in an address space that the application does not have access to; the kernel also maintains a list of capabilities in such memory.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The performance cost of address space switching limits the practicality of this approach in systems with complex interactions between objects, but it is used in current operating systems for objects that are not accessed frequently or that are not expected to perform quickly.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] If the firmware does not support protection mechanisms, it is possible to simulate protection at a higher level, for example by simulating capabilities by manipulating page tables, but there are performance implications.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Lack of hardware support may not be an issue, however, for systems that choose to use language-based protection.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] An important kernel design decision is the choice of the abstraction levels where the security mechanisms and policies should be implemented.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Kernel security mechanisms play a critical role in supporting security at higher levels.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] One approach is to use firmware and kernel support for fault tolerance (see above), and build the security policy for malicious behavior on top of that (adding features such as cryptography mechanisms where necessary), delegating some responsibility to the compiler.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Approaches that delegate enforcement of security policy to the compiler and/or the application level are often called *language-based security*.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The lack of many critical security mechanisms in current mainstream operating systems impedes the implementation of adequate security policies at the application abstraction level.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, a common misconception in computer security is that any security policy can be implemented in an application regardless of kernel support.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] According to Mars Research Group developers, a lack of isolation is one of the main factors undermining kernel security.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] They propose their driver isolation framework for protection, primarily in the Linux kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Typical computer systems today use hardware-enforced rules about what programs are allowed to access what data.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The processor monitors the execution and stops a program that violates a rule, such as a user process that tries to write to kernel memory.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In systems that lack support for capabilities, processes are isolated from each other by using separate address spaces.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Calls from user processes into the kernel are regulated by requiring them to use one of the above-described system call methods.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] An alternative approach is to use language-based protection.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In a language-based protection system, the kernel will only allow code to execute that has been produced by a trusted language compiler.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The language may then be designed such that it is impossible for the programmer to instruct it to do something that will violate a security requirement.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Examples of systems with language-based protection include JX and Microsoft's Singularity.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Edsger Dijkstra proved that from a logical point of view, atomic lock and unlock operations operating on binary semaphores are sufficient primitives to express any functionality of process cooperation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Nonetheless, this approach is generally held to be lacking in terms of safety and efficiency, whereas a message passing approach is more flexible.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A number of other approaches (either lower- or higher-level) are available as well, with many modern kernels providing support for systems such as shared memory and remote procedure calls.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The idea of a kernel where I/O devices are handled uniformly with other processes, as parallel co-operating processes, was first proposed and implemented by Brinch Hansen (although similar ideas were suggested in 1967).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In Hansen's description of this, the "common" processes are called *internal processes*, while the I/O devices are called *external processes*.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Similar to physical memory, allowing applications direct access to controller ports and registers can cause the controller to malfunction, or system to crash.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] With this, depending on the complexity of the device, some devices can get surprisingly complex to program, and use several different controllers.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Because of this, providing a more abstract interface to manage the device is important.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This interface is normally done by a device driver or hardware abstraction layer.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Frequently, applications will require access to these devices.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The kernel must maintain the list of these devices by querying the system for them in some way.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This can be done through the BIOS, or through one of the various system buses (such as PCI/PCIE, or USB).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Using an example of a video driver, when an application requests an operation on a device, such as displaying a character, the kernel needs to send this request to the current active video driver.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The video driver, in turn, needs to carry out this request.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is an example of inter-process communication (IPC).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The above listed tasks and features can be provided in many ways that differ from each other in design and implementation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The principle of *separation of mechanism and policy* is the substantial difference between the two main philosophies of microkernels and monolithic kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Here a *mechanism* is the support that allows the implementation of many different policies, while a *policy* is a particular "mode of operation".
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Because the mechanism and policy are separated, the policy can be easily changed to, e.g., require the use of a security token.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel instead tends to include many policies, therefore restricting the rest of the system to rely on them.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Computer scientist Per Brinch Hansen argued in favour of separation of mechanism and policy.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The failure to properly fulfill this separation is one of the major causes of the lack of substantial innovation in existing operating systems, a problem common in computer architecture.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic design is induced by the "kernel mode"/"user mode" architectural approach to protection (technically called hierarchical protection domains), which is common in conventional commercial systems; in fact, every module needing protection is therefore preferably included into the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] While monolithic kernels execute all of their code in the same address space (kernel space), microkernels try to run most of their services in user space, aiming to improve maintainability and modularity of their codebase.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most kernels do not fit exactly into one of these categories, but are rather found in between these two designs.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] More exotic designs such as nanokernels and exokernels are available, but are seldom used for production systems.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The Xen hypervisor, for example, is an exokernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In a monolithic kernel, all OS services are part of the kernel and run in kernel mode, thus also residing in the same memory area.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This approach provides rich and powerful hardware access.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] UNIX developer Ken Thompson stated that "it is in [his] opinion easier to implement a monolithic kernel".
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The main disadvantages of monolithic kernels are the dependencies between system components – a bug in a device driver might crash the entire system, for example – and the fact that large kernels can become very difficult to maintain.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Thompson also stated that "It is also easier for [a monolithic kernel] to turn into a mess in a hurry as it is modified".
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels, which have traditionally been used by Unix-like operating systems, contain all the operating system core functions and the device drivers.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel is one single program that contains all of the code necessary to perform every kernel-related task.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Every part that is to be accessed by a program that cannot be put in a library is in the kernel space, including drivers, schedulers, memory management, file systems, and network stacks.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many system calls are provided to applications, to allow them to access all those services.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A monolithic kernel, while initially loaded with subsystems that may not be needed, can be tuned to a point where it is as fast as or faster than one that was specifically designed for the hardware, although more relevant in a general sense.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most work in the monolithic kernel is done via system calls.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] These are interfaces, usually kept in a tabular structure, that access some subsystem within the kernel, such as disk operations.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Essentially, calls are made within programs and a checked copy of the request is passed through the system call.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic Linux kernel can be made extremely small not only because of its ability to dynamically load modules but also because of its ease of customization.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, there are some versions that are small enough to fit together with a large number of utilities and other programs on a single floppy disk and still provide a fully functional operating system (one of the most popular of which is muLinux).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This ability to miniaturize its kernel has also led to a rapid growth in the use of Linux in embedded systems.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels consist of the core functions of the operating system and the device drivers with the ability to load modules at runtime.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] They provide rich and powerful abstractions of the underlying hardware.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] They provide a small set of simple hardware abstractions and use applications called servers to provide more functionality.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This particular approach defines a high-level virtual interface over the hardware, with a set of system calls to implement operating system services such as process management, concurrency and memory management in several modules that run in supervisor mode.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A microkernel that is designed for a specific platform or device is only ever going to have what it needs to operate.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The microkernel approach consists of defining a simple abstraction over the hardware, with a set of primitives or system calls to implement minimal OS services such as memory management, multitasking, and inter-process communication.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other services, including those normally provided by the kernel, such as networking, are implemented in user-space programs, referred to as *servers*.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels are easier to maintain than monolithic kernels, but the large number of system calls and context switches might slow down the system because they typically generate more overhead than plain function calls.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Only parts that really require being in a privileged mode are in kernel space, such as IPC (Inter-Process Communication), a basic scheduler or scheduling primitives, basic memory handling, and basic I/O primitives.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many critical parts are now running in user space, including the complete scheduler, memory handling, file systems, and network stacks.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels were invented as a reaction to traditional "monolithic" kernel design, whereby all system functionality was put in one static program running in a special "system" mode of the processor.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In the microkernel, only the most fundamental of tasks are performed at this level, such as being able to access some (not necessarily all) of the hardware, manage memory and coordinate message passing between the processes.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some systems that use microkernels are QNX and GNU Hurd.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In the case of QNX and GNU Hurd, user sessions can be entire snapshots of the system itself, or "views" as it is referred to.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Most microkernels use a message passing system to handle requests from one server to another.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The message passing system generally operates on a port basis with the microkernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] As an example, if a request for more memory is sent, a port is opened with the microkernel and the request sent through.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Once within the microkernel, the steps are similar to system calls.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The rationale was that it would bring modularity in the system architecture, which would entail a cleaner system that is easier to debug or dynamically modify, customizable to users' needs, and higher performing.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Microkernels are part of operating systems like GNU Hurd, MINIX, MkLinux, QNX and Redox OS.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Although microkernels are very small by themselves, in combination with all their required auxiliary code they are, in fact, often larger than monolithic kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Advocates of monolithic kernels also point out that the two-tiered structure of microkernel systems, in which most of the operating system does not interact directly with the hardware, creates a not-insignificant cost in terms of system efficiency.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels normally provide only the minimal services such as defining memory address spaces, inter-process communication (IPC) and process management.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other functions, such as running hardware processes, are not handled directly by microkernels.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Proponents of microkernels point out those monolithic kernels have the disadvantage that an error in the kernel can cause the entire system to crash.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] With a microkernel, however, if a kernel process crashes, it is still possible to prevent a crash of the system as a whole by merely restarting the service that caused the error.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Other services provided by the kernel such as networking are implemented in user-space programs referred to as *servers*.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Servers allow the operating system to be modified by simply starting and stopping programs.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] For a machine without networking support, for instance, the networking server is not started.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The task of moving in and out of the kernel to move data between the various applications and servers creates overhead that is detrimental to the efficiency of microkernels in comparison with monolithic kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Disadvantages in the microkernel exist, however.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The disadvantages for microkernels are extremely context-based.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] As an example, they work well for small single-purpose (and critical) systems because if not many processes need to run, then the complications of process management are effectively mitigated.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A microkernel allows the implementation of the remaining part of the operating system as programs running in user mode, and the use of different operating systems on top of the same unchanged kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] It is also possible to dynamically switch among operating systems and to have more than one active simultaneously.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] As the computer kernel grows, so grows the size and vulnerability of its trusted computing base, in addition to its memory footprint.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This is mitigated to some degree by perfecting a virtual memory system, but not all computer architectures have virtual memory support.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] To reduce the kernel's footprint, extensive editing has to be performed to carefully remove unneeded code, which can be very difficult with non-obvious interdependencies between parts of a kernel with millions of lines of code.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] By the early 1990s, due to the various shortcomings of monolithic kernels versus microkernels, monolithic kernels were considered obsolete by virtually all operating system researchers.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] As a result, the design of Linux as a monolithic kernel rather than a microkernel was the topic of a famous debate between Linus Torvalds and Andrew Tanenbaum.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] There is merit on both sides of the argument presented in the Tanenbaum–Torvalds debate.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Monolithic kernels are designed to have all of their code in the same address space (kernel space), which some developers argue is necessary to increase the performance of the system.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Some developers also maintain that monolithic systems are extremely efficient if well written.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The monolithic model tends to be more efficient through the use of shared kernel memory, rather than the slower IPC system of microkernel designs, which is typically based on message passing.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The performance of microkernels was poor in both the 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Studies that empirically measured the performance of these microkernels did not analyze the reasons of such inefficiency.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The explanations of this data were left to "folklore", with the assumption that they were due to the increased frequency of switches from "kernel-mode" to "user-mode", to the increased frequency of inter-process communication and to the increased frequency of context switches.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] In fact, as guessed in 1995, the reasons for the poor performance of microkernels might as well have been: (1) an actual inefficiency of the whole microkernel *approach*, (2) the particular *concepts* implemented in those microkernels, and (3) the particular *implementation* of those concepts.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Therefore it remained to be studied if the solution to build an efficient microkernel was, unlike previous attempts, to apply the correct construction techniques.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Hybrid kernels are used in some commercial operating systems, including most versions of Microsoft Windows to date (NT 3.1, NT 3.5, NT 3.51, NT 4.0, 2000, XP, Vista, 7, 8, 8.1, 10 and 11).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Apple's macOS uses a hybrid kernel called XNU, which is based upon code from OSF/1's Mach kernel (OSFMK 7.3) and FreeBSD's monolithic kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Hybrid kernels are similar to microkernels, except they include some additional code in kernel-space to increase performance.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] These kernels represent a compromise that was implemented by some developers to accommodate the major advantages of both monolithic and microkernels.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] These types of kernels are extensions of microkernels with some properties of monolithic kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Unlike monolithic kernels, these types of kernels are unable to load modules at runtime on their own.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This implies running some services (such as the network stack or the filesystem) in kernel space to reduce the performance overhead of a traditional microkernel, but still running kernel code (such as device drivers) as servers in user space.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Many traditionally monolithic kernels support loadable kernel modules.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The most well known of these kernels is the Linux kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The modular kernel essentially can have parts of it that are built into the core kernel binary or binaries that load into memory on demand.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A code-tainted module has the potential to destabilize a running kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] By contrast, it is possible to write a driver for a microkernel in a completely separate memory space and test it before "going" live.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] When a kernel module is loaded, it accesses the monolithic portion's memory space by adding to it what it needs, therefore opening the doorway to possible pollution.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Modules, generally, communicate with the kernel using a module interface of some sort.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] The interface is generalized (although particular to a given operating system) so it is not always possible to use modules.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Often the device drivers may need more flexibility than the module interface affords.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Essentially, it is two system calls and often the safety checks that only have to be done once in the monolithic kernel now may be done twice.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A nanokernel delegates virtually all services – including even the most basic ones like interrupt controllers or the timer – to device drivers to make the kernel memory requirement even smaller than a traditional microkernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Exokernels are a still-experimental approach to operating system design.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] They differ from other types of kernels in limiting their functionality to the protection of and multiplexing of access to the raw hardware, providing no hardware abstractions on top of which to develop applications.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] This separation of hardware protection from hardware management enables application developers to determine how to make the most efficient use of the available hardware for each specific program.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Exokernels in themselves are extremely small.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Nonetheless, they are accompanied by library operating systems (see also unikernel), providing application developers with the functionalities of a conventional operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A major advantage of exokernel-based systems is that they can incorporate multiple library operating systems, each exporting a different API, for example one for high level UI development and one for real-time control.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] A multikernel operating system treats a multi-core machine as a network of independent cores, as if it were a distributed system.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] It does not assume shared memory but rather implements inter-process communications as message passing.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p01] Barrelfish was the first operating system to be described as a multikernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Strictly speaking, an operating system (and thus, a kernel) is not *required* to run a computer.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Programs can be directly loaded and executed on the "bare metal" machine, provided that the authors of those programs are willing to work without any hardware abstraction or operating system support.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Most early computers operated this way during the 1950s and early 1960s, which were reset and reloaded between the execution of different programs.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Eventually, small ancillary programs such as program loaders and debuggers were left in memory between runs, or loaded from ROM.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] As these were developed, they formed the basis of what became early operating system kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] The "bare metal" approach is still used today on some video game consoles and embedded systems, but in general, newer computers use modern operating systems and kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] In 1969, the RC 4000 Multiprogramming System introduced the system design philosophy of a small nucleus "upon which operating systems for different purposes could be built in an orderly manner", what would be called the microkernel approach.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the decade preceding Unix, computers had grown enormously in power – to the point where computer operators were looking for new ways to get people to use their spare time on their machines.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] One of the major developments during this era was time-sharing, whereby a number of users would get small slices of computer time, at a rate at which it appeared they were each connected to their own, slower, machine.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] The development of time-sharing systems led to a number of problems.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] One was that users, particularly at universities where the systems were being developed, wanted to hack the system to get more CPU time.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] For this reason, security and access control became a major focus of the Multics project in 1965.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Another ongoing issue was properly handling computing resources: users spent most of their time staring at the terminal and thinking about what to input instead of actually using the resources of the computer, and a time-sharing system should give the CPU time to an active user during these periods.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Finally, the systems typically offered a memory hierarchy several layers deep, and partitioning this expensive resource led to major developments in virtual memory systems.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] The Commodore Amiga was released in 1985, and was among the first – and certainly most successful – home computers to feature an advanced kernel architecture.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] The AmigaOS kernel's executive component, *exec.library*, uses a microkernel message-passing design, but there are other kernel components, like *graphics.library*, that have direct access to the hardware.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] There is no memory protection, and the kernel is almost always running in user mode.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Only special actions are executed in kernel mode, and user-mode applications can ask the operating system to execute their code in kernel mode.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] During the design phase of Unix, programmers decided to model every high-level device as a file, because they believed the purpose of computation was data transformation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] For instance, printers were represented as a "file" at a known location – when data was copied to the file, it printed out.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Other systems, to provide a similar functionality, tended to virtualize devices at a lower level – that is, both devices *and* files would be instances of some lower level concept.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Virtualizing the system at the file level allowed users to manipulate the entire system using their existing file management utilities and concepts, dramatically simplifying operation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] As an extension of the same paradigm, Unix allows programmers to manipulate files using a series of small programs, using the concept of pipes, which allowed users to complete operations in stages, feeding a file through a chain of single-purpose tools.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although the end result was the same, using smaller programs in this way dramatically increased flexibility as well as ease of development and use, allowing the user to modify their workflow by adding or removing a program from the chain.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the Unix model, the *operating system* consists of two parts: first, the huge collection of utility programs that drive most operations; second, the kernel that runs the programs.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Over the years the computing model changed, and Unix's treatment of everything as a file or byte stream no longer was as universally applicable as it was before.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although a terminal could be treated as a file or a byte stream, which is printed to or read from, the same did not seem to be true for a graphical user interface.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Even if network communication can be compared to file access, the low-level packet-oriented architecture dealt with discrete chunks of data and not with whole files.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] As the capability of computers grew, Unix became increasingly cluttered with code.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] It is also because the modularity of the Unix kernel is extensively scalable.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] While kernels might have had 100,000 lines of code in the seventies and eighties, kernels like Linux, of modern Unix successors like GNU, have more than 13 million lines.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Modern Unix-derivatives are generally based on module-loading monolithic kernels.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Examples of this are the Linux kernel in the many distributions of GNU, IBM AIX, as well as the Berkeley Software Distribution variant kernels such as FreeBSD, DragonFly BSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD, and macOS.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apart from these alternatives, amateur developers maintain an active operating system development community, populated by self-written hobby kernels that mostly end up sharing many features with Linux, FreeBSD, DragonflyBSD, OpenBSD, or NetBSD kernels and/or being compatible with them.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apple first launched its classic Mac OS in 1984, bundled with its Macintosh personal computer.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Apple moved to a nanokernel design in Mac OS 8.6.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Against this, the modern macOS (originally named Mac OS X) is based on Darwin, which uses a hybrid kernel called XNU, which was created by combining the 4.3BSD kernel and the Mach kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Microsoft Windows was first released in 1985 as an add-on to MS-DOS.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Because of its dependence on another operating system, initial releases of Windows, prior to Windows 95, were considered an operating environment (not to be confused with an operating system).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] This product line continued to evolve through the 1980s and 1990s, with the Windows 9x series adding 32-bit addressing and pre-emptive multitasking; but ended with the release of Windows Me in 2000.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Microsoft also developed Windows NT, an operating system with a very similar interface, but intended for high-end and business users.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] This line started with the release of Windows NT 3.1 in 1993, and was introduced to general users with the release of Windows XP in October 2001—replacing Windows 9x with a completely different, much more sophisticated operating system.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] This is the line that continues with Windows 11.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] The architecture of Windows NT's kernel is considered a hybrid kernel because the kernel itself contains tasks such as the Window Manager and the IPC Managers, with a client/server layered subsystem model.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] It was designed as a modified microkernel, as the Windows NT kernel was influenced by the Mach microkernel but does not meet all of the criteria of a pure microkernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Supervisory program or supervisor is a computer program, usually part of an operating system, that controls the execution of other routines and regulates work scheduling, input/output operations, error actions, and similar functions and regulates the flow of work in a data processing system.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Historically, this term was essentially associated with IBM's line of mainframe operating systems starting with OS/360.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] In other operating systems, the supervisor is generally called the kernel.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] In the 1970s, IBM further abstracted the supervisor state from the hardware, resulting in a hypervisor that enabled full virtualization, i.e. the capacity to run multiple operating systems on the same machine totally independent of each other.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Hence the first such system was called *Virtual Machine* or *VM*.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Although Mach, developed by Richard Rashid at Carnegie Mellon University, is the best-known general-purpose microkernel, other microkernels have been developed with more specific aims.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] The L4 microkernel family (mainly the L3 and the L4 kernel) was created to demonstrate that microkernels are not necessarily slow.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Newer implementations such as Fiasco and Pistachio are able to run Linux next to other L4 processes in separate address spaces.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/kernel-operating-system-p02] Additionally, QNX is a microkernel that is principally used in embedded systems, and the open-source software MINIX, while originally created for educational purposes, is now focused on being a highly reliable and self-healing microkernel OS.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] The concept of observability was introduced by the Hungarian-American engineer Rudolf E.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] A dynamical system designed to estimate the state of a system from measurements of the outputs is called a *state observer* for that system, such as Kalman filters.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] Consider a physical system modeled in state-space representation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] A system is said to be **observable** if, for every possible evolution of state and control vectors, the current state can be estimated using only the information from outputs (physically, this generally corresponds to information obtained by sensors).
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] In other words, one can determine the behavior of the entire system from the system's outputs.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] On the other hand, if the system is not observable, there are state trajectories that are not distinguishable by only measuring the outputs.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] For time-invariant linear systems in the state space representation, there are convenient tests to check whether a system is observable.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] is equal to n , then the system is observable.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] The rationale for this test is that if n columns are linearly independent, then each of the n state variables is viewable through linear combinations of the output variables y .
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] Observability is a sufficient and necessary condition for the design of continuous-time state observers.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] where ${\mathcal {C}}(\mathbb {R$ is the set of continuous functions from $\mathbb {R}$ to $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] Since the system is observable if and only if $\operatorname {rank} ({\mathcal {O}})=n$ , the system is observable if and only if N is the zero subspace.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] A slightly weaker notion than observability is *detectability*.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] A system is detectable if all the unobservable states are stable.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] Detectability conditions are important in the context of sensor networks.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] Functional observability is an important concept because it determines the sufficient and necessary condition under which a *functional observer* (also known as a Darouach observer ) can be designed to asymptotically estimate $\mathbf {z} (t)$ .
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] Under certain conditions, functional observability and output controllability are mathematical duals, implying that the problems of estimating and controlling a linear functional $\mathbf {z} (t)$ (rather than the full state $\mathbf {x} (t)$ ) are equivalent under a system transformation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] where $\varphi$ is the state-transition matrix.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] It is possible to determine a unique $x(t_{0})$ if $M(t_{0},t_{1})$ is nonsingular.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] In fact, it is not possible to distinguish the initial state for $x_{1}$ from that of $x_{2}$ if $x_{1}-x_{2}$ is in the null space of $M(t_{0},t_{1})$ .
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] The system is observable in $[t_{0},t_{1}]$ if and only if there exists an interval $[t_{0},t_{1}]$ in $\mathbb {R}$ such that the matrix $M(t_{0},t_{1})$ is nonsingular.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] Where $x\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ the state vector, $u\in \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ the input vector and $y\in \mathbb {R} ^{p}$ the output vector. $f,g,h$ are to be smooth vector fields.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] Early criteria for observability in nonlinear dynamic systems were discovered by Griffith and Kumar, Kou, Elliot and Tarn, and Singh.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] There also exist an observability criteria for nonlinear time-varying systems.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] Observability may also be characterized for steady state systems (systems typically defined in terms of algebraic equations and inequalities), or more generally, for sets in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] Just as observability criteria are used to predict the behavior of Kalman filters or other observers in the dynamic system case, observability criteria for sets in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ are used to predict the behavior of data reconciliation and other static estimators.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/observability] In the nonlinear case, observability can be characterized for individual variables, and also for local estimator behavior rather than just global behavior.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Logs that record program usage (such as a server log) or operating-system events primarily of interest to a system administrator (see for example *Event Viewer*) fall into a terminological gray area.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Tracing is primarily used for anomaly detection, fault analysis, debugging or diagnostic purposes in distributed software systems, such as microservices or serverless functions.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Software tracing is a tool for developers to gather information for debugging.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] This information is used both during development cycles and post-release.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Unlike event logging, software tracing usually does not have the concept of a "class" of event or an "event code".
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] OpenTelemetry is a CNCF open source project that provides comprehensive support for distributed tracing.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Some vendors including Datadog, Dynatrace, New Relic, Splunk also offer tracing SaaS services.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Google and Meta have developed their own tracing frameworks, named Dapper and Canopy respectively.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] In operating systems, tracing can be used in situations (such as booting) where some of the technologies used to provide event logging may not be available.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Linux offers system-level and user-level tracing capabilities with kernel markers and LTTng. ftrace also supports Linux kernel tracing. syslog is another tool in various operating systems for logging and tracing system messages.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] FreeBSD and SmartOS employ DTrace for tracing in both user space and kernel space.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] In embedded software, tracing also requires special techniques for efficient instrumentation and logging and low CPU overhead.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Trace generation of method calls can be done with source code instrumentation, runtime information collection, or under debugger control.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Tracing macros, aspect-oriented programming and related instrumentation techniques can be employed.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Libraries used in source code send data to an agent or directly to the collection component.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] To model execution trees, ISVis converts a rooted tree into a directed acyclic graph while Jinsight utilizes the call frame principle to gather and represent cumulative information about traces.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] The primary visualization method is the swimlane view, which is exemplified by tools like Jaeger and often includes annotations and key-value attributes.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Despite its widespread use, this design lacks rigorous justification and users frequently face challenges like missing features and confusing navigation.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Alternatives to swimlane views exist, like Jaeger’s service dependency view or SkyWalking’s List, Tree, and Table views.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Aggregate visualizations are also used for analyzing large volumes of traces, with systems like Canopy offering queryable metrics and Jaeger providing trace comparison features.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Event logging provides system administrators with information useful for diagnostics and auditing.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] The different classes of events that will be logged, as well as what details will appear in the event messages, are often considered early in the development cycle.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Many event logging technologies allow or even require each class of event to be assigned a unique "code", which is used by the event logging software or a separate viewer (e.g., Event Viewer) to format and output a human-readable message.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] This facilitates localization and allows system administrators to more easily obtain information on problems that occur.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Because event logging is used to log high-level information (often failure information), performance of the logging implementation is often less important.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] A special concern, preventing duplicate events from being recorded "too often" is taken care of through event throttling.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Difficulties in making a clear distinction between event logging and software tracing arise from the fact that some of the same technologies are used for both, and further because many of the criteria that distinguish between the two are continuous rather than discrete.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Enabling or disabling tracing during runtime often necessitates the inclusion of extra data in the binary.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] This can lead to performance degradation, even when tracing is not active.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] The overhead of tracing depends on the used framework and the activated features; in production servers, there is a trade-off between how fine-grained the tracing is and the incurred overhead.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] If tracing is enabled or disabled at compile-time, collecting trace data from a client's system hinges on their willingness and capability to install a version of the software specifically enabled for tracing, and subsequently replicate the issue.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Tracing in software typically demands high standards of robustness, not only in the accuracy and reliability of the trace output but also in ensuring that the process being traced remains uninterrupted.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] Given its low-level nature, tracing can generate a large volume of messages.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] To mitigate performance issues, it's often necessary to have the option to deactivate software tracing, either at the time of compilation or during run-time.
[src:ebpf-security-deep/tracing-software] In proprietary software, tracing data may include sensitive information about the product's source code.
